d Mrs. J. C. Wallace had\nas their guests during the New\nYear holidays Mrs. Isabel Ed\nwards, Mr. and Mfr Dan Bryant,\nMr. and Mrs. R A. Wells and\nMasses Mary Wells, Jean McCall<\nand Joan and Nancy Myrahan, alll\nof Jacksonville.\nBy Mrs. Bryan Whitfield\nMrs. J. G. Caldwell and Misses\nJune and Peggy Caldwell were in\nGainesville Thursday.\n\nNew Year holiday visitors of\nMr. and Mrs. J. L.Williams were\nMr. and Mrs. J. D- Williams and\nItheir children, James and Kathryn\n;of Milton. Additional Sunday\nguest!' of Mr. and Mrs. Williams\n;were Mr. and Mrs. j'Mse Stewart\n;of Jacksonville.\n\nMr. and Mrs. Leslie Bradley\nand son, Johnnie, of Raiford\nspent the past week-end with Mr.\nand Mrs. J^ M- Bradley.\nWhen Mr. and Mrs. J. A. Bou\nvier returned from their Christ\nmas vacation with relatives in\nMiami and in Mclntosh la* Thur\nsday they were accompained by\nMrs. Cecil Mc\u00dfea and Andre',\nPatricia and Eleanor Mc\u00dfae who\nwere their luncheon guests^\n\nMr. and Mrs\u00ae R. W. Brannen\nvisited Miss Pauline Brannen in\nJack&ivilh New Year's Day.\n\nMr. and Mrs- J. A. Bouvier\nwent to Jacksonville ^Monday to\nspend several hours with friends,\nMr. and Mrs. J. C. Epting, who\nwere en ^oute from Ft. Myers to\n'^heir home in Spartanburg, S. C.,\nIMrs. L. F.lhapman and Mrs. M.\nGriner went to Jacksonville\nwith Mr- and ^rs. Bouvier.\n\nFollowing a week's visit, with\nDr. and Mrs. D. L. Nix,\nJ. Sharpe and Rodney White re\ntun^d to their home in Com\nmerce, Georgia Monday.\n\nDr. and Mr's. D.^L. Nix attend\ned the Otomge Bowl game in\nMiami New Year's Day.\n'l\nMr. and Mrs- Wallace Kelly of\n'Ocilla, Georgia were visitors of\nMr. and hv^. J. R. Chasteen Wed\nnesday and Thursday of last wfyk\nFUNERAL SERVICES FOR\nMRS M. R. HOLMES\nFuneral services for Mrs. M. R.\nHolmes of Raiford was held at\nthe Ellzy Chapel near Dukes,\nThursday, December 30, with\nRev. L. A. Shepherd conducting\nthe burial services.\nMrs. Holms was visiting relat\nives in Leesburg when taken\nwith a heart attack and injuries\nfrom a subsequent fall. She\nwas in the Leesburg hospital for\nseveral days following the attach\nShe died Tuesday night, Decem\nber 28, and the body was return\ned to her home in Raiford where\nit remained several hours Thurs\nday prior to interment.\n\nWANTED \u2014To buy 15 bushels\nof Porta Rica Potato Seed at once.\nRobert Sandel\nWorthington, Fla.\n\nMisses Frances Riherd and\nJanice Bridwell returned to their\nstudies at F. S. U. in Tallahassee\nMonday they were accompained\nby their mothers, Mrs. T. Mm\nRiherd and Mrs. J. W. Bridwell,\nwho also attended the inaugurat\nion of the new Governor.\nFarm News\nBy: William J. Cowen,\nCounty &gent\nKEEP TOBACCO BEDS AND\nFIELDS ALWAYS RID\nOF ICACH MOSAIC\nDestroy any old tobacco plants\nstill alive, especially these in the\nvicinity of your new beds, and\nsave yourself some grief from\netch mosaic disease and aphids.\nThis is the suggestion of Sta+e\nPlant Board wooers to toba&i\ngrowers who ai@ now planting\ntheir tobacco beds. Both etch\nmosaic and aphids have been a\n(l^at during the past year or\ntwo.\n4 Ordinarly, frost has killed old\ntobacco plants before now, but\nthis winter has been unusually\nmild. The warm weather also\nhas been favorable for aphids.\nIn addition to damaging plants by\nfeeding on them, aphids spread\nmosaic disease.\nPlant Board inspectors and\nFred C lark, tobacco agronomist\nwittyhe Agricultural Experiment\nStation, also urge farmers to\ngrow their own tobacco plants to\nlessen the danger' of introducing\netch mosaic into their plantings.\nThe disease is not transmitted on\nthe seed.\nGeorgia a authorities have a\nquarantine against tobacco plants\nproduced in Broward, Palm Beach\nand Hillsborough counties. Plants\nproduced in all other Florida\ncounties may be shipped into\nGeorgia after inspection by the\nState Plant Board, if accompanied\nby certificates of inspection.\nGrowers desiring inspection\nshould contact J. C. \u00aeGoodwin,\nnursery inspector with the State\n;Plant Board in Gainesville.\nEMPHASIS ON MEAT\nPRODUCTION\nFarmerfoshfyuld bear in mind\nthat meat production is expected\nto be short and^stillin high de\nmand in 1949. V This should tell\ngood farm managers to plan to\nproduce as much meat, b6th beef\nand pork, as can be economically\nproduced on his far m depending\nupon its acreage which can be de\nvoted to feed crops and its physi\ncal setup such as fences and\nequipment. Don't overstock or\nproduce more animals than feed,\nbut make plans to produce quality\nanimals through breeding and\nmanagement and feed. Quality\nalways pays and particularly so in\nperiods when supply and demand\nare practically equal with incomes\nhigh in off-farming accupations.\nNow is the time to become quality\nconcious in pi@paration for that\nday even though it dosn't come\nthis year. Management includ\ning proper feeding products is one\nof the most important factors in\nmaking livestock a paying enter\nprise. If animals are allowed to\nbecome wormy or unthrifty be\ncause of lack of feed or running\nin infested pastures, they will re\nquire more feed and costmore to\ngetyhem back in a thrifty con\ndition than wogd have been res\nSquired to keep them from getting\nI unthrifty. Any tyme feed or\nI mon yin ost can be saved by\npractices which prevent this con-\nj dition the margin of profit is in\ncrease In periods of business\nI recession su?n little saving can\nI mean the difference between pay\nling and losing enterprises^ Good\nmanagement is tty difference be\ntween good and average farmers,\nand the business recession expect\ned by most experts will further\naccen^ate ,is difference wren\nn^longer mistakes in manage\nment could be covered by high\nprices. Plan to produce quality\nanimals with the le^st amount of\nfee^ both home grown and bought\npossible keeping in mind that\nquality is the important consider\nation.","height":"24816","width":"17028"}}
